#compdef rust-mdbg
# ============================================================================
# rust-mdbg - minimizer-space de Bruijn graph genome
#              assembler for long+accurate reads (Rust,
#              MIT)
#
# Authors : Baris Ekim + Rayan Chikhi
# Upstream: https://github.com/ekimb/rust-mdbg
# crates  : rust-mdbg (binary: rust-mdbg)
#
# `rust-mdbg` is an ultra-fast minimizer-space de
# Bruijn graph (mdBG) assembler geared toward
# long-and-accurate sequencing reads (PacBio HiFi,
# Oxford Nanopore Q20+, ONT Q30 R10.4.1). The
# assembler is fast because it operates in
# minimizer-space, meaning that:
#   - reads are represented as ordered lists of
#     minimizers (not strings of nucleotides)
#   - the de Bruijn graph itself is built over
#     minimizer-tuples (k-min-mers) rather than k-mers
#   - the final assembly is also a minimizer-space
#     representation
#   - a separate conversion step (the `to_basespace`
#     binary shipped alongside `rust-mdbg`) emits the
#     base-space (ACGT) assembly when needed
#
# Published in Bioinformatics 2021: "minimizer-space
# de Bruijn graphs: Whole-genome assembly of long
# reads in minutes on a personal computer", Ekim +
# Chikhi + Berger, Cell Systems 2021.
#
# Usage:
#   rust-mdbg [OPTIONS] <reads-file>
#
# Args:
#   <reads-file>            - input FASTA / FASTQ
#                              file (also accepts
#                              .gz / .lz4
#                              compression)
#
# Required parameters (typical values):
#   -k <k>                  - k-min-mer length
#                              (typical 21-31)
#   -l <l>                  - l-mer (minimizer) length
#                              (typical 14-21)
#   -n <n>                  - tuple length for
#                              read bucketing
#   -t <t>                  - POA path weight
#                              threshold
#   -d, --density <f>       - density threshold for
#                              minimizer selection
#                              (typical 0.001)
#
# Output:
#   -p, --prefix <path>     - output prefix for GFA
#                              + .sequences files
#
# Optional flags (structopt):
#       --debug             - show base-space
#                              sequence + minimizer-
#                              space representation
#                              per read
#       --uhs <file>        - universal k-mer file
#                              for UHS-based selection
#       --lcp <file>        - core substring file for
#                              LCP-based selection
#       --minabund <N>      - minimum k-min-mer
#                              abundance
#       --distance <N>      - distance parameter
#       --correction-threshold <i>
#                           - error-correction
#                              threshold
#       --error-correct     - run the error-
#                              correction pass
#       --restart-from-postcor
#                           - restart from post-
#                              correction
#                              intermediate
#       --reference         - reference-mode (single
#                              high-quality input)
#       --bf                - use BLOOM FILTER for
#                              fast k-min-mer
#                              counting (this file's
#                              canonical-library
#                              hook)
#       --skiphpc           - skip homopolymer-
#                              compression
#       --no-basespace      - skip the post-assembly
#                              minimizer -> base-space
#                              conversion step
#       --read-stats <file> - emit per-read stats
#                              file
#       --syncmers          - use syncmer selection
#                              instead of minimizer
#       -s <s>              - syncmer parameter
#       --lmer-counts <file> - precomputed l-mer
#                              counts file
#       --lmer-counts-min <N>
#       --lmer-counts-max <N>
#       --presimp <f>       - pre-simplification
#                              threshold (0.0-1.0)
#       --threads <N>       - parallel threads
#                              (default available
#                              CPUs)
#   -h, --help              - print help
#   -V, --version           - print version
#
# The Bloom filter lane is built on `xx-bloomfilter =
# "0.10.0"` (declared at upstream Cargo.toml HEAD as
# a direct dep, imported as `use xx_bloomfilter::
# Bloom`), the canonical Rust Bloom filter
# implementation by Akira Yoshikuma + the xx-
# bloomfilter contributors. The crate provides:
#   - configurable false-positive rate target
#   - automatic bit-array sizing
#   - XXHash-based hashing (compatible with
#     BurntSushi-style XXHash usage at Axis 222)
#   - constant-time `insert(item)` + `check(item)`
#     operations
#
# The Bloom filter data structure (Burton Bloom,
# CACM 1970) provides probabilistic set membership
# with no false negatives + tunable false-positive
# rate. The structure is *the* foundational
# probabilistic data structure - the conceptual
# predecessor to Cuckoo filters, Count-Min Sketch,
# HyperLogLog, and the whole family of approximate
# data structures.
#
# rust-mdbg uses Bloom filters in the `--bf` mode
# for fast k-min-mer dedup during the graph
# construction pass. Without `--bf`, the assembler
# uses an exact HashMap<KminMer, Abundance> for
# counting; with `--bf`, a Bloom filter pre-filters
# the keys + only high-confidence-non-singleton
# k-min-mers reach the exact HashMap. The trade-off
# is faster construction (no false-negatives from
# the Bloom layer) at the cost of slightly
# inflated abundance counts (rare false positives
# from the Bloom side).
#
# The `RacyBloom` wrapper in src/main.rs
# intentionally allows data races on the Bloom
# filter bits to maximize multi-threaded insertion
# throughput - safe because Bloom filter's monotonic
# "set bit -> still set" invariant means concurrent
# writes that conflict simply set the same bit
# twice with no semantic loss.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 257 :: Bloom filter probabilistic data structure
#              (set membership with tunable FP rate)
# Round 1469 :: Rust slot 1 of 4 :: OPENS Axis 257
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis
# (proposed):
#   Rust    : xx-bloomfilter               - Akira
#                                            Yoshikuma's
#                                            canonical
#                                            Rust Bloom
#                                            filter
#                                            crate;
#                                            XXHash-
#                                            based
#                                            hashing
#   Go      : bits-and-blooms/bloom        - the
#                                            community
#                                            canonical
#                                            Go Bloom
#                                            filter
#                                            library;
#                                            depended on
#                                            by
#                                            CockroachDB,
#                                            Caddy
#                                            certificate
#                                            store
#   TS/Node : bloom-filters                - Node Bloom
#                                            + Cuckoo +
#                                            Count-Min +
#                                            HyperLogLog
#                                            umbrella by
#                                            Folkvir
#
# Bloom filter is an algorithm-bound axis - Burton
# Bloom's 1970 CACM paper defines the algorithm
# with a single hash family + parameter triple (n,
# m, k). Compliant implementations produce the same
# false-positive rate for the same parameter triple,
# modulo hash function choice (different libraries
# use different hash families; the wire format is
# not standardized across implementations).
#
# Structural commentary on the canonical libraries:
#   - xx-bloomfilter (Rust): XXHash-based; constant-
#     time insert + check; optional persistence to
#     disk
#   - bits-and-blooms/bloom (Go): renamed from
#     willf/bloom in 2021 after the original author
#     handed off maintenance; the de-facto Go Bloom
#     filter library; depended on by CockroachDB +
#     Caddy + InfluxDB
#   - bloom-filters (Node): Folkvir's umbrella
#     covering Bloom + Cuckoo + Count-Min Sketch +
#     HyperLogLog + Quotient Filter + Vacuum Filter +
#     Counting Bloom + Scalable Bloom
#
# Cross-language interop at the algorithm level - same
# (n, m, k) parameters + same hash family produces
# byte-identical bit arrays. Wire format is not
# standardized; lanes intentionally don't try to
# interop at the binary-format level.
# ============================================================================

_rust-mdbg() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '--debug[show base-space + minimizer-space representation]' \
        '--uhs[universal k-mer file]:file:_files' \
        '--lcp[core substring file]:file:_files' \
        '(-p --prefix)'{-p,--prefix}'[output prefix]:path:_files -W "$PWD" -P "" -S ""' \
        '(-k)-k[k-min-mer length]:k:' \
        '(-l)-l[l-mer (minimizer) length]:l:' \
        '(-n)-n[tuple length for read bucketing]:n:' \
        '(-t)-t[POA path weight threshold]:t:' \
        '(-d --density)'{-d,--density}'[density threshold]:f:' \
        '--minabund[minimum k-min-mer abundance]:N:' \
        '--distance[distance parameter]:N:' \
        '--correction-threshold[error-correction threshold]:i:' \
        '--error-correct[run error-correction pass]' \
        '--restart-from-postcor[restart from post-correction intermediate]' \
        '--reference[reference-mode (single high-quality input)]' \
        '--bf[use Bloom filter for fast k-min-mer counting]' \
        '--skiphpc[skip homopolymer compression]' \
        '--no-basespace[skip minimizer->base-space conversion]' \
        '--read-stats[emit per-read stats file]:file:_files' \
        '--syncmers[use syncmer selection]' \
        '(-s)-s[syncmer parameter]:s:' \
        '--lmer-counts[precomputed l-mer counts file]:file:_files' \
        '--lmer-counts-min[lmer counts min]:N:' \
        '--lmer-counts-max[lmer counts max]:N:' \
        '--presimp[pre-simplification threshold (0.0-1.0)]:f:' \
        '--threads[parallel thread count]:N:' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[print version]' \
        '1:reads file:_files -g "*.{fa,fasta,fq,fastq,fa.gz,fastq.gz,fa.lz4,fastq.lz4}"'
}

_rust-mdbg "$@"
